ening chapters review state-of-the-art ultrasound imaging and molecular genetics and focus on the new patient—the fetus. From here, the efficacy of fetal therapy, the problem of assessing long-term viability, the ethical issues involved in both clinical practice and medical research, and the legal rights of the new patients and their parents are examined. The final chapter “Are Fetuses Becoming Children?” brings a fresh philosophical perspective to the question of a fetus’s status and rights.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aMedical. 4aPhilosophy. 7aMEDICAL / Ethics.2bisacsh1 aCameron, Alan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClewell, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavies, Dawn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGriener, Glenn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGriener, Glenn, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHarder, Joyce, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoar, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeyserlingk, Edward W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aManchester, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aManco-Johnson, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeier, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMilner, Ruth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNicholson, Stuart, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNimrod, Carl, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNimrod, Carl, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPreto